Night,
soft
belly
of
a
pregnant
Negress,
throbs
evenly
against
the

torso
of
the
South.
Night
throbs
a
womb-song
to
the
South.
Cane

and
cotton-fields,
pine
forests,
cypress
swamps,
saw-mills,
and
factories

are
fecund
at
her
touch.
Night's
womb-song
sets
them
singing.
Night

winds
are
the
breathing
of
the
unborn
child
whose
calm
throbbing
in

the
belly
of
a
Negress
sets
them
somnolently
singing.
Hear
their
song.

land.

streets

and
still.
White
paint
on
the
wealthier

houses
has
the
chill
blue
glitter
of
distant
stars.
Negro
cabins
are
a

purple
blur.
Broad
Street

deserted.
Winds
stir

corru

rope

Chesterfield

Chero-Cola
cardboard

From

side
door
two
men
come
out.
Pause,
for
a
last

word
and
then
they
say
good
night.
Soon
they
melt
in
shadows
thicker

than
they.
Way
off
down
the
street
four
figures
sway
beneath
iron

awnings

form
a
sort
of
corridor
that
imperfectly
echoes
and

jumbles
what
they
say.
A
fifth
form

them.
They
turn
into
the

road
that
leads
to
Halsey's
workshop.
The
old
building
is
phosphor

escent
above
deep
shade.
The
figures
pass
through
the
double
door.

Night
winds
whisper
in
the
eaves.
Sing
weirdly
in
the
ceiling
cracks.

curls
